        "section_value": "Chief Complaint\nNeck pain following a motor vehicle accident.\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports neck pain following a motor vehicle accident, characterized by forward head and neck movement with associated pain. He describes the pain as not constant, but exacerbated by head movement. He has attempted to manage the pain with ibuprofen with limited relief. He denies any recent trauma prior to the accident. He reports headaches and pain that radiates to his upper back and shoulders. He reports experiencing pain with neck flexion, extension, and rotation. He denies any hearing or visual disturbances. He did not seek emergency room care following the accident and reports no swelling or bruising to the neck.\nFindings\nPhysical examination reveals positive tenderness to palpation of the soft tissues of the neck. Pain is elicited with neck flexion, extension, and rotation. Pain is also noted with lateral neck bending. There are no signs of fracture or bony abnormalities on radiographic examination.\nAssessment\nThe patient's presentation is consistent with whiplash-associated neck pain.\nPlan",
